Load data

Downloading data

raw_dir <- here("data/_raw/")
data_loc <- "https://gdc-hub.s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/download/"
download_file(raw_dir, 
              data_loc, 
              data_file = "TCGA-BRCA.star_fpkm.tsv.gz", 
              new_file_name = "gene_expression_fpkm.tsv.gz")
download_file(raw_dir, 
              data_loc, 
              data_file = "TCGA-BRCA.clinical.tsv.gz", 
              new_file_name = "phenotypes.tsv.gz")

Loading data

Phenotype data

phenotypes_subset <- phenotypes |> 
  select(sample, 
         gender.demographic,
         ajcc_pathologic_stage.diagnoses,
         age_at_diagnosis.diagnoses, 
         ethnicity.demographic, 
         days_to_death.demographic, 
         vital_status.demographic,
         treatment_or_therapy.treatments.diagnoses,
         primary_diagnosis.diagnoses, 
         prior_malignancy.diagnoses, 
         year_of_diagnosis.diagnoses)

Gene expression data

Sampling 2000 random genes

gene_expression_subset <- gene_expression |> 
  sample_n(size = 2000)

Pivoting longer

gene_expression_subset_long_format <- gene_expression_subset |> 
  pivot_longer(cols = !Ensembl_ID, 
               names_to = "sample", 
               values_to = "gene_expression")

Joining the two datasets

loaded_data <- gene_expression_subset_long_format |> 
  inner_join(phenotypes_subset, 
             join_by(sample))

Cleaning the data

Renaming the columns

clean_data <- loaded_data |> 
  rename_with(~ str_replace(., "\\..*", "")) |> 
  rename("ensembl_id" = "Ensembl_ID", 
         "cancer_stage" = "ajcc_pathologic_stage")

Tidying treatment and therapy

clean_data <- clean_data |> 
  mutate(treatment_or_therapy = str_remove_all(treatment_or_therapy, 
                                               pattern = "[\\[\\]\\']")) |> 
  separate_wider_delim(treatment_or_therapy,
                       delim = ", ",
                       names = c("treatment", "therapy"))

Saving the clean data

write_tsv(x = clean_data, 
          file = here("data/02_dat_clean.tsv.gz"), na = "NA")

Augmenting the data

Age at diagnosis from days to years

clean_data <- clean_data  |> 
  mutate(age_at_diagnosis_years = age_at_diagnosis/365.25)

Age grouping

clean_data = clean_data |> 
  mutate(age_group = case_when(20 < age_at_diagnosis_years & age_at_diagnosis_years <= 30 ~ "(20,30]",
                               30 < age_at_diagnosis_years & age_at_diagnosis_years <= 40 ~ "(30,40]",
                               40 < age_at_diagnosis_years & age_at_diagnosis_years <= 50 ~ "(40,50]",
                               50 < age_at_diagnosis_years & age_at_diagnosis_years <= 60 ~ "(50,60]",
                               60 < age_at_diagnosis_years & age_at_diagnosis_years <= 70 ~ "(60,70]",
                               70 < age_at_diagnosis_years & age_at_diagnosis_years <= 80 ~ "(70,80]",
                               80 < age_at_diagnosis_years & age_at_diagnosis_years <= 90 ~ "(80,90]"))

Years from diagnosis to death

clean_data <- clean_data  |> 
  mutate(years_from_diagnosis_to_death = (days_to_death/365.25))

Age at death in years

clean_data <- clean_data  |> 
  mutate(age_at_death_years = age_at_diagnosis_years + years_from_diagnosis_to_death)

Year of death

clean_data <- clean_data  |> 
  mutate(year_of_death = year_of_diagnosis+years_from_diagnosis_to_death)

Write to tsv

clean_data |> write_tsv(file = here("data/03_dat_aug.tsv.gz"), na = "NA")

Here, it becomes clear that the most prominent cancer stage represented in the data is stage IIA, while Stage II and Stage IB are more sparse.

gender_ethnicity_overview

It is hereby noticiable that the majority of the ethnicities represented are categorised as “not hispanic or latino”. This is a lack within in the dataset, which does not specify specific ethnicities, but rather categorizes patient as either latino or not latino.

It should be noted that the y-axis here is proportion, and that the ethnicities are represented as a fraction of the data within each gender. This is important so as to avoid any confusion on how well each gender is represented in the data (as seen in the table1 above, men only make up 1.1% of the dataset).

combined_plot

This graph shows slight differences, but it is not very clear whether there is a real effect of each treatment. Therefore, it would be beneficial to represent this data in a different way, as seen below. Here, we can create a new column for the treatment combinations, and stratify this data by vitality status.

Looking at whether therapy, treatment, both or neither have any effect on whether the patient lives or not

combined_data <- data |>
  mutate(
    combined_category = case_when(
      therapy == "yes" & treatment == "yes" ~ "Both",
      therapy == "no" & treatment == "yes" ~ "Treatment Only",
      therapy == "yes" & treatment == "no" ~ "Therapy Only",
      therapy == "no" & treatment == "no" ~ "Neither",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    )
  ) |>
  filter(!is.na(combined_category), !is.na(vital_status))
treatment_vs_therapy <- ggplot(combined_data, 
       aes(x = combined_category, 
           fill = vital_status)) +

    fill = "Vital Status"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(size=12),
    axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold"),

  )
  

treatment_vs_therapy

Here we see that, as common sense would dictate, there is a larger percentage of patients who die when they do not receive any treatment, and it appears that therapy is the most effective of the two.

Percentage of dead and alive people of each gender for each ethnicity.

data_summary <- data |>
  filter(!is.na(gender) & !is.na(vital_status) & !is.na(ethnicity) & ethnicity != "not reported") |>
  group_by(gender, ethnicity, vital_status) |>
  summarise(count = n(), .groups = "drop") |>
  group_by(ethnicity, gender) |>
  
  mutate(total_count = sum(count)) |>
  
  ungroup() |>
  
  mutate(percentage = (count / total_count) * 100) |>
  mutate(percentage = ifelse(gender == "female",
                               percentage,
                               -1*percentage)) |>

  bind_rows(tibble(gender = "male", ethnicity = "hispanic or latino", vital_status = "Dead", percentage = 0))
gender_ethnicity_vitality <- ggplot(data_summary, 
       aes(x = ethnicity, 
           y = ifelse(gender == "female", percentage, -percentage), 
           fill = vital_status)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge", width = 0.7, alpha=0.7) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "black", linewidth = 0.5) +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Alive" = "#66c2a5", "Dead" = "#fc8d62")) + 
  facet_wrap(~ gender, scales = "free_x", ncol = 2) + 
  labs(
    title = "Vitality by Ethnicity and Gender",
    x = NULL,
    y = "Percentage",
    caption = "Data from BRCA at: https://xenabrowser.net/",
    fill = "Vital Status"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold"),
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14, face = "bold"),
    strip.text = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),
    legend.position = "top"
  )


gender_ethnicity_vitality

Again, it should be noted that this data is shown as a percentage, as a very small subset of the data represents men. However, it can still be noted that a greater percentage of non-hispanic people in the study have died, as opposed to latino patients. This is true for both genders, and may explain why the researchers have divided the patient ethnicities into these two groups.

Survival time by cancer stage

Let’s take a look at survival times for the different cancer stages.

data |> 
  filter(cancer_stage != "Stage IB" & 
           cancer_stage != "Stage II" &
           vital_status == "Dead") |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = cancer_stage, 
                       y = years_from_diagnosis_to_death,
                       fill = cancer_stage)
         ) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(x = "Cancer stages",
       y = "Years until death",
       caption = "Data from BRCA at: https://xenabrowser.net/",
       title = "Years Until Death by Cancer Stage") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = 'none')

In general it seems the worse the cancer stage of a patient is when diagnosed, the shorter until the patient dies. There is however a weird insight, namely that patients diagnosed with stage IIB cancer lives longer than patients with stage IIA cancer, which is counter intuitive. This could be an artifact of the fact that this study is right-censored.

Let’s take a look at the amount of dead and alive patients across cancer stage

data |> 
  drop_na(cancer_stage) |>
  filter(cancer_stage != "Stage IB" & cancer_stage != "Stage II") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = cancer_stage, fill = vital_status)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Alive" = "lightgreen", "Dead" = "maroon")) +
  labs(
    title = "Vital Status by Cancer Stage",
    x = "Cancer Stage",
    y = "Count", 
    caption = "Data from BRCA at: https://xenabrowser.net/",
    fill = "Vital Status"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

We can see that most patients are diagnosed in stage IIA and stage IIB, which is also the stages with the most patients surviving.

Performing a PCA

Pivoting the dataset into a wide format:

data_pivot <- data |>
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = ensembl_id,
    values_from = gene_expression
  )

Selecting the gene expression data from all the genes, and removing the genes which have a gene expression og 0 for all patients. Then the principal component analysis is performed using prcomp:

pca_fit <- data_pivot |> 
  select(starts_with("ENSG")) |> 
  select(where(~ any(. != 0))) |> 
  prcomp(scale = TRUE)

The eigenvalues are extracted in a tidy format, and used to make plot axes labels for the PCA plot, which consists of the principal component and the proportion of variance explained for this PC:

pca_plot_axes_labels <- pca_fit |>
  tidy("eigenvalues") |>
  mutate(lbl = str_c("PC", PC, ", VE = ", round(percent*100,2), "%")) |> 
  pull("lbl")

The PCA plot is produced, stratified on the cancer stage:

pca_plot <- pca_fit |> 
  augment(data_pivot) |> 
  filter(abs(.fittedPC1) < 50 & abs(.fittedPC2) < 50) |> 
  ggplot(aes(.fittedPC1, .fittedPC2, color = cancer_stage)) +
  geom_point(size = 1.5) +
  theme_half_open(12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=27), 
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 20), 
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 20)) +
  background_grid() + 
  labs(title = "PCA: Scores Plot of gene expression",
    x = pluck(pca_plot_axes_labels, 1),
    y = pluck(pca_plot_axes_labels, 2), 
    color = "Cancer stage", 
    caption = "Data from BRCA at: https://xenabrowser.net/") + 
  scale_colour_viridis_d()

pca_plot

Because there is only one big cluster in the PCA we cannot say anything about if the patients are grouped together by the gene expression of certain genes.

We save the plot as a png file:

Scree plot

Creating a scree plot of the principal components to see how much information is explained by each of the PCs:

scree_plot <- pca_fit |>
  tidy("pcs") |> 
  mutate(percent = percent * 100) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = PC,
             y = percent)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
  geom_col(colour = "black",
           alpha = 0.5, 
           fill = "coral") +
  theme_half_open(12) + 
  background_grid() + 
  theme(panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(), 
        plot.title = element_text(size=27), 
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 20), 
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 20)) +
  labs(title = "Scree Plot", 
       x = "Principal Component", 
       y = "Variance Explained (%)", 
       caption = "Data from BRCA at: https://xenabrowser.net/") +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(1, 100), ylim = c(0, 20)) 


scree_plot

When looking at the Scree plot, we can see that the first two PCs only explain about 22% of the variance, meaning that not a lot of the information is retained in the PCA plot.

Grouping and nesting cancer stage and performing PCA on each group

This testing is preformed to see if there is any gene expression clustering within the cancer stages

Nesting data by cancer stage

nested_data <- data_pivot |> 
  group_by(cancer_stage) |> 
  nest()

Performing PCA on each group within the nested data

pca_results <- nested_data |> 
  mutate(
    pca = map(data, ~ {
      .x |> 
        select(starts_with("ENSG")) |> 
        select(where(~ any(. != 0))) |>
        scale() |> 
        prcomp()
    })
  ) |> 
  mutate(
    pca_aug = map2(pca, data, ~augment(.x, data = .y))
  )

Selecting the pca data and unnesting

pca_plot_data <- pca_results |> 
  select(cancer_stage, pca_aug)  |>
  unnest(pca_aug)

Plotting each of the stage PCAs

ggplot(pca_plot_data, aes(x = .fittedPC1, y = .fittedPC2, color = vital_status)) +
    geom_point(size = 1.5) +
    facet_wrap(~ cancer_stage, scales = "free") +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 15) +
    labs(
      title = "PCA Results by Cancer Stage",
      x = "Principal Component 1",
      y = "Principal Component 2",
      color = "Vital Status"
    ) +
    theme(
      legend.position = "bottom",
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
    )

When looking at these plots it is not evedint that any of the stages contain clusters. Though we want to look further into the Stage IIIB

Linear modelling

Plot of years at diagnosis vs age at diagnosis, by cancer stage.

The plots highlight the correlation between the age of patient diagnosed and when the patient dies and by which diagnosis (stage).

Filter and factorize the data

data_factored <- data |>
  filter(
    !is.na(age_at_diagnosis_years) & 
    !is.na(years_from_diagnosis_to_death)
  ) |>
  mutate(
    cancer_stage = factor(
      cancer_stage,
      levels = c(
        "Stage I", 
        "Stage IA", 
        "Stage IB", 
        "Stage II", 
        "Stage IIA", 
        "Stage IIB", 
        "Stage III", 
        "Stage IIIA", 
        "Stage IIIB",
        "Stage IIIC", 
        "Stage IV"
      )
    )
  )

Calculate correlations for each cancer stage

correlations <- data_factored |>
  group_by(cancer_stage) |>
  summarize(
    correlation = cor(age_at_diagnosis_years, 
                      years_from_diagnosis_to_death, 
                      use = "complete.obs"),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

Creating the plot

data_factored |>
  ggplot(aes(x = age_at_diagnosis_years, y = years_from_diagnosis_to_death, color = cancer_stage)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, size = 1.2) + 
  scale_color_manual(
    values = colorRampPalette(c("lightcoral", "darkred"))(9)
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ cancer_stage, scales = "free") +
  geom_text(
    data = correlations,
    aes(x = Inf, y = Inf, label = paste("cor.r =", round(correlation, 2))),
    inherit.aes = FALSE,
    hjust = 1.2, vjust = 1.5, size = 3
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Age at Diagnosis vs Years to Death by Cancer Stage",
    x = "Age at Diagnosis (years)",
    y = "Years to Death",
    color = "Cancer Stage"
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    limits = c(20, 90), 
    breaks = seq(20, 90, by = 10)
  ) + 
  scale_y_continuous(
    limits = c(0, 15), 
    breaks = seq(0, 15, by = 2)
  ) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)
  )

Separate code for calculation of the correlations and mean age of diagnosis and mean days to death:

summary_stats_by_stage <- data |>
  filter(
    !is.na(age_at_diagnosis_years) & 
    !is.na(years_from_diagnosis_to_death)
  ) |> 
  group_by(cancer_stage) |>
  summarize(
    mean_age = mean(age_at_diagnosis_years, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_years_to_death = mean(years_from_diagnosis_to_death, na.rm = TRUE),
    correlation = cor(age_at_diagnosis_years, 
                      years_from_diagnosis_to_death, 
                      use = "complete.obs"),
    .groups = "drop" 
  )

Setup of linear model to describe years from diagnosis to death

filtered_data <- data |>
  filter(
    !is.na(cancer_stage),
    treatment != "not reported"
  )
lm_model <- lm(
  years_from_diagnosis_to_death ~ 
    cancer_stage + 
    age_at_diagnosis_years + 
    treatment + 
    prior_malignancy,
  data = filtered_data
)

Filter out “not reported” and NA values in cancer_stage, and ensure no missing values in key variables

filtered_data <- data |>
  filter(
    !is.na(cancer_stage),
    treatment != "not reported",
    !is.na(age_at_diagnosis_years),
    !is.na(years_from_diagnosis_to_death)
  )

filtered_data <- filtered_data |>
  mutate(predicted_years_to_death = predict(lm_model))
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = predicted_years_to_death, 
                          y = years_from_diagnosis_to_death)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, 
              intercept = 0, 
              color = "red", 
              linetype = "dashed") + 
  labs(
    title = "Predicted vs Actual Years to Death",
    x = "Predicted Years to Death",
    y = "Actual Years to Death"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
filtered_data |>
  ggplot(aes(x = predicted_years_to_death, 
             y = years_from_diagnosis_to_death, 
             color = treatment)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, 
              intercept = 0, 
              color = "red", 
              linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(
    title = "Predicted vs Actual Years to Death by Treatment",
    x = "Predicted Years to Death",
    y = "Actual Years to Death",
    color = "Treatment"
  )  + 
  theme_minimal()

Plot actual vs. predicted, faceted by treatment and prior malignancy

filtered_data |>
  ggplot(aes(x = predicted_years_to_death,
